#import "template.typ": *

#let metadata = (
  title: "Phase 1 Consolidation and Radio Essentials",
  unit: "Group A (3-Axis) | Phase 1 — Lesson 9 | E1–E10, E13 assessed",
  author: "C.Moroney",
  version: "v1.0.0",
)

#let lesson = (
title: [Phase 1 Consolidation and Radio Essentials]

,aim: [
Confirm all Phase 1 flight elements to solo standard in a connected flight, formally assess E8 (Take Off), and introduce the radio procedures required for safe circuit flying.
]

,overview: [
This lesson is the Phase 1 milestone check and the confirmation of readiness for circuits.

The first part of the ground brief reviews Phase 1 theory and briefs the assessment sequence. The second part covers the radio and transponder procedures needed in the circuit. Full E13 competency — airspace detail, area procedures, and radio failure — is formally assessed later in Phase 3. In the air, the student demonstrates all Phase 1 elements in a connected sequence with relevant radio calls attempted throughout. The instructor observes and assesses; does not coach.

Because E10 requires ceiling >3000 ft AGL, this condition applies to the full assessment flight. If conditions do not allow E10, E7 and E10 may be assessed separately on a different day; remaining elements may be assessed in lower conditions.
]

,learning_outcomes: [
#text(size:12pt)[*Knowledge*]
- Demonstrate recall of key theory from all Phase 1 elements when questioned during debrief
- Explain the PAT and LARI workcycles and identify when each applies
- Describe the CTAF call structure and the recommended radio calls for circuit operations at the home aerodrome
- Explain transponder operation and the standard codes
- Describe the initial actions for a radio failure

#text(size:12pt)[*Skills*]
- Conduct a complete takeoff sequence independently to S standard, including pre-takeoff safety brief
- Maintain straight and level at cruise and slow cruise to S standard
- Climb and descend to S standard using correct workcycles
- Execute level turns at 15° and 30° AoB to S standard
- Demonstrate slow flight management and pre-stall recognition to S standard
- Execute steep turns at 45° and 60° AoB to S standard; recover from a spiral dive entry
- Demonstrate turning stall recognition and recovery to S standard
- Transmit all recommended circuit radio calls with correct structure and phraseology
- Operate the transponder correctly throughout the flight

#text(size:12pt)[*Non-Technical Skills*]
- [SA] Maintains LARI scan and lookout throughout without prompting; HASSELL completed before E9/E10 sequence
- [TEM] Identifies and verbalises threats throughout without prompting; radio used as an alerted see-and-avoid tool
- [HF] Applies IMSAFE; demonstrates correct startle response management in stalling scenarios
- [CRM] Operates confidently as pilot-in-command; uses correct control handover
]

,theory_knowledge: [
- Consolidation of all Phase 1 reading
- VHF Radio — CTAF calls, transponder *(Pg 55–58, 62–63)*
- Air Legislation — airspace classifications, radio requirements *(Pg 256)*
- Human Factors — communication errors *(Pg 45)*
]

,ground_brief_topics: [
Total time: 40 minutes \
Equipment required: Student training record, progress checklist, local VTC \

*Phase 1 Theory Review and Assessment Brief* (10 minutes)
- Brief verbal Q&A: key theory from E2–E10 and E8
- Student briefs today's planned flight as pilot-in-command: departure, tasks, return, TEM threats
- Assessment criteria confirmed: all elements assessed today; standards required
- Pre-solo Air Legislation exam: confirm study is underway; must be passed before first solo
- Weather check: ceiling >3000 ft AGL required to include E10; confirm before proceeding

*Radio Essentials for Circuit Operations* (20 minutes)

_Radio equipment and operation_
- PTT, frequency selector, squelch, volume, standby frequency
- Confirm serviceability before flight; intercom check
- Transponder: modes (A, C, S); standard codes (1200, 7700, 7600, 7500); ALT before taxi if possible

_CTAF procedure_
- CTAF concept: listening watch; transmit clearly and concisely
- Call structure: callsign, position, altitude, intentions; listen before transmitting
- Radio as an alerted see-and-avoid tool: calls build the traffic picture

_Circuit call sequence at GCSFT_
- Taxi; runway crossing; entering and lining up; base; clear of runway

_Radio failure — initial actions_
- Confirm failure: volume, squelch, PTT, frequency
- Transmit blind; squawk 7600; continue with increased vigilance in see-and-avoid; land normally

*Pre-Solo Requirements Reminder* (10 minutes)
- Pre-solo Air Legislation exam: must be passed before first solo
- S standard required across all Phase 1 elements — today's flight assesses this
- Note: full E13 assessment (airspace, area procedures) occurs in Phase 3 Lesson 12
]

,ground_tasks:[
#text(size:12pt)[*Instructor*]
- Review student training record before the lesson; identify any elements requiring focus
- Spot check of weather and NOTAMs with student; confirm ceiling >3000 ft AGL for E10; if not, plan split assessment

#text(size:12pt)[*Student*]
- Complete IMSAFE self-assessment and operations whiteboard
- Obtain NAIPS TAF; check BOM radar; brief conditions and suitability
- Lead full pre-flight inspection independently; complete documentation
- Deliver pre-takeoff safety brief before taxi independently; include EFATO plan
- Make all circuit radio calls without instructor prompting
]

,in_flight_tasks:[
#text(size:12pt)[*E8 Takeoff Assessment*]
Student conducts the complete takeoff sequence to S standard. Instructor assesses:
- Pre-takeoff safety brief delivered correctly before taxi
- Directional control maintained throughout ground roll
- Smooth lift-off; Vy maintained +10/−0 kts
- After-takeoff checks completed without prompting
- Departure radio call made correctly

#text(size:12pt)[*Connected Sequence Assessment*]
Instructor observes and assesses — does not lead or prompt. Student conducts a connected flight demonstrating all Phase 1 elements:

- Transit to training area: correct radio call; traffic awareness verbalised
- Straight and level at cruise: heading ±5°, altitude ±200 ft, ball centred
- Transition to slow cruise using PAT; maintain with LARI
- Vy climb to nominated altitude; level off using APT
- Cruise descent to nominated altitude; level off using PAT
- 15° and 30° turns in both directions; climbing and descending turns
- *HASSELL check*: student completes before the high-risk manoeuvre sequence begins
- *Slow flight and pre-stall recognition (E7)*: HASSELL complete; symptoms identified; recovery executed
- *Advanced turning (E9)*: student completes own HASSELL and begins without prompting:
  - 45° steep turn left and right: bank ±5°, altitude ±150 ft, rollout ±10°
  - 60° steep turn left and right: bank ±5°, altitude ±150 ft, rollout ±10°
  - Spiral dive: instructor initiates entry briefly; student recovers without coaching
- *Scenario based stalling (E10)*: continuing from altitude after E9:
  - Turning stall at 30° AoB: student enters; recovers without prompting; height loss ≤300 ft
  - Go-around scenario: student prevents stall entry without prompting
- Return to aerodrome: student may fly the circuit under instructor direction; student on flight controls throughout; all radio calls without prompting
- Transponder operated throughout with correct codes

#text(size:12pt)[*Instructor Action During Flight*]
- Intervene only for safety — not to coach or prompt
- Note all elements as S, C, or NC in the training record
- If a safety concern arises: take control, resolve, return control to student
]

,common_errors:[
- *Element-specific errors*: Refer to common errors in each preceding lesson plan.
- *HASSELL omitted before E9/E10*: NC for both elements — non-negotiable.
- *Incorrect radio call structure*: callsign, position, altitude, intentions — every time.
- *Fixating on radio at expense of flying*: Attitude and trim first; LARI scan continues; radio after.
- *E9 overbanking not corrected*: Active correction required; demonstrate habit before rollout.
]

,post_flight:[
- *Student Self-Assessment* (10 min): Student leads the debrief; self-assesses each element including E9 and E10. Instructor listens before providing feedback.
- *Instructor Feedback* (15 min):
  - Provide assessment result for each element: S, C, or NC with specific comments.
  - If any element is NC: explain what was observed; state the remediation plan before Phase 2.
  - Confirm Phase 1 milestone: "You are ready for circuit training" or "We will do one more Phase 1 consolidation targeting [specific elements]."
  - Comment on radio: call structure correct? Traffic awareness demonstrated?
- *Next Steps*: If all elements at S standard — begin Phase 2 (Stage C1) at next suitable opportunity. Confirm Air Legislation exam preparation target.
]

,standards_for_progression:[
*All of the following must be at S standard before Phase 2 commences:*
- *E2 — Effects of Controls*: Smooth, positive inputs; correct trim technique
- *E3 — Straight and Level*: Heading ±5°, altitude ±200 ft, ball ±1/4 width
- *E4 — Climbing*: Vy +10/−0 kts, heading ±5°; lowers nose every 500 ft; correct level-off
- *E5 — Descending*: All descent types ±10 kts; correct level-off
- *E6 — Basic Turning*: Bank ±5°, altitude ±150 ft, rollout ±10°; pre-turn lookout without prompting
- *E7 — Slow Flight and Stall Recognition*: HASSELL complete; pre-stall symptoms identified before full stall; impending stall recovery ≤300 ft height loss; correct rudder on wing drop without prompting
- *E8 — Take Off*: Pre-takeoff brief delivered before taxi; directional control maintained; Vy established; after-takeoff checks complete
- *E9 — Advanced Turning*: 60° steep turns ±5° bank, ±150 ft; spiral dive recovery correct and unprompted; HASSELL before sequence
- *E10 — Scenario Based Stalling*: Turning stall recovery ≤300 ft, rudder on wing drop without prompting; go-around and EFATO stall prevention; elevator trim stall recovery
*These elements may be at a P standard*
- *E13 — Radio Essentials*: Circuit call sequence transmitted with correct structure; transponder operated correctly; initial radio failure actions known; instructor assistance or prompting acceptable
- *Note*: Full E13 competency (airspace, area procedures) assessed in Phase 3 Lesson 12.
- *Outcome*: All elements recorded in student training record as S (or C). NC elements require remediation before Phase 2 commences.
]

,safety:[
- *Weather*: Ceiling >3000 ft AGL and smooth air required to include E9 and E10; if conditions are marginal, E9/E10 may be assessed on a separate day and remaining elements assessed today. Wind \<15 knots.
- *Altitude*: E10 above 2500 ft AGL; all stall recoveries complete above 2500 ft AGL; E9 above 2000 ft AGL; all other elements above 1000 ft AGL
- *Emergency Procedures*: EFATO brief completed; HASSELL before the high-risk manoeuvre sequence; forced landing area preselected
- *TEM*:
  - Assessment flight — instructor must remain non-interventionist while safety-ready
  - If student shows significant stress affecting safety, end assessment mode; return to coaching
  - Spiral dive: instructor brief on ground before flight; take control immediately if entry is uncontrolled
  - Monitor weather throughout; conditions must remain suitable for all planned exercises
]

,homework:[
- Complete Pre-Solo Air Legislation Exam preparation:
  - VMC minimums, right-of-way rules, aerodrome procedures and markings, airspace classes
  - Review RAAus FOM Section 2.06 (Student Pilot Certificate requirements)
- Read Bob Tait's RAAus Study Guide:
  - VHF Radio: Pg 55–58, 62–63 (CTAF procedures, radio calls, transponder)
  - Air Legislation: Pg 256 (airspace classifications)
  - Human Factors: Pg 45 (communication errors)
- Practise circuit radio calls aloud using the GCSFT CTAF sequence
- Reflect:
  - "Which Phase 1 element is your strongest? Which needs the most work before you go solo?"
  - "If your radio failed while downwind in the circuit, what would you do?"
]
)

#show: body => lesson_plan(metadata, lesson, body)
